<!-- HERO -->
<section id="hero">
  <div class="hero-inner">
    <div class="hero-badge">✦ Visual Learning Guide</div>
    <h1 class="hero-title">What <span>IS</span> Quantum<br>Computing?</h1>
    <p class="hero-sub">Classical computers use bits — 0 or 1. Quantum computers use <strong>qubits</strong> that can be both at once. This changes everything.</p>

    <div class="coin-demo">
      <div class="coin-wrapper">
        <div class="coin-classical" style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,#f59e0b,#d97706);border-color:#f59e0b;box-shadow:0 0 20px rgba(245,158,11,0.4);">0
          <span class="bit-label">Bit = 0</span>
        </div>
        <div class="coin-label" style="margin-top:2.5rem;">Definite State</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-divider">VS</div>
      <div class="coin-wrapper">
        <div class="coin-qubit">⚛</div>
        <div class="coin-label">Superposition</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-divider">VS</div>
      <div class="coin-wrapper">
        <div class="coin-classical" style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,#8b5cf6,#6d28d9);border-color:#8b5cf6;box-shadow:0 0 20px rgba(139,92,246,0.4);">1
          <span class="bit-label">Bit = 1</span>
        </div>
        <div class="coin-label" style="margin-top:2.5rem;">Definite State</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p style="color:var(--text-muted);font-size:0.9rem;max-width:520px;margin:0 auto 3rem;">A spinning coin is neither heads nor tails — it's <em>both simultaneously</em>. A qubit works the same way. Until you look (measure it), it exists in multiple states at once.</p>

    <div class="hero-scroll">
      <span>Scroll to explore</span>
      <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none"><path d="M8 3v10M3 9l5 5 5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg>
    </div>
